HEADWORD: Fear
<hw>Fear</hw> <pr>(f⟦emac⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A variant of
<er>Fere</er>, a mate, a companion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fear</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fear
<hw>Fear</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>fer</ets>, <ets>feer</ets>,
<ets>fere</ets>, AS. <ets>f⟦aemac⟧r</ets> a coming suddenly upon, fear,
danger; akin to D. <ets>vaar</ets>, OHG. <ets>f⟦amac⟧ra</ets> danger, G.
<ets>gefahr</ets>, Icel. <ets>f⟦amac⟧r</ets> harm, mischief, plague, and
to E. <ets>fare</ets>, <ets>peril</ets>. See <er>Fare</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A painful emotion or passion excited by the expectation
of evil, or the apprehension of impending danger; apprehension; anxiety;
solicitude; alarm; dread.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The degrees of this passion, beginning with the most
moderate, may be thus expressed, -- <contr>apprehension</contr>,
<ex>fear</ex>, <contr>dread</contr>, <contr>fright</contr>,
<contr>terror</contr>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fear</qex> is an uneasiness of the mind, upon the thought of
future evil likely to befall us.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where no hope is left, is left no <qex>fear</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Script.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Apprehension of
incurring, or solicitude to avoid, God's wrath; the trembling and awful
reverence felt toward the Supreme Being.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>Respectful reverence for men of authority or worth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will put my <qex>fear</qex> in their hearts.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
xxxii. 40.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will teach you the <qex>fear</qex> of the Lord.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
xxxiv. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Render therefore to all their dues; tribute to whom tribute is due
. . . <qex>fear</qex> to whom <qex>fear</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. xiii.
7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which causes, or which is the object of,
apprehension or alarm; source or occasion of terror; danger;
dreadfulness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There were they in great fear, where no <qex>fear</qex> was.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. liii. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>fear</qex> of your adventure would counsel you to a more
equal enterprise.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>For fear</b></col>, <cd>in apprehension lest.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>For fear</xex> you ne'er see chain nor money more.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fear</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fear
<hw>Fear</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Feared</conjf> <pr>(f⟦emac⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fearing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>feren</ets>,
<ets>faeren</ets>, to frighten, to be afraid, AS. <ets>f⟦aemac⟧ran</ets>
to terrify. See <er>Fear</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
feel a painful apprehension of; to be afraid of; to consider or expect
with emotion of alarm or solicitude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>fear</qex> no evil, for thou art with me.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. xxiii. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>With subordinate clause.⟦br⟧
<q>I greatly <qex>fear</qex> my money is not safe.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<q>I almost <qex>fear</qex> to quit your hand.</q> <rj><qau>D.
Jerrold.</qau></rj></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have a reverential awe of; to be solicitous to
avoid the displeasure of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Leave them to God above; him serve and <qex>fear</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be anxious or solicitous for; now replaced by
<altname>fear for</altname>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sins of the father are to be laid upon the children, therefore
. . . I <qex>fear</qex> you.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To suspect; to doubt.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ay what else, <qex>fear</qex> you not her courage?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To affright; to terrify; to drive away or prevent
approach of by fear.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Fear</qex> their people from doing evil.</q>
<rj><qau>Robynson (More's Utopia).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tush, tush! <qex>fear</qex> boys with bugs.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To apprehend; dread; reverence;
venerate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fear</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fear
<hw>Fear</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be in apprehension of evil; to
be afraid; to feel anxiety on account of some expected evil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I exceedingly <qex>fear</qex> and quake.</q> <rj><qau>Heb. xii.
21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fearer</ent>⟦br⟧
